KONA,SUV,@scraverX,"On the matter of the rear suspension, and this is something you might not know. The Hybrid (Not available in the US) and the EV use the Multi link McPherson strut like the AWD and N-Line.
I will note some markets (Australia for example) only get AWD in the N Line. Hybrid is FWD only.

For me, the side looks a lot better on the N-line where all the plastic is body coloured, then the design lines make a LOT more sense.",12,KONA,0
KONA,SUV,@inwiththenew,"I drove one as a rental car for a week and really enjoyed driving it, especially with all the safety features",114,KONA,4
KONA,SUV,@RyanEmeryLovesCars,"We rented a 2025 Hyundai Kona SEL FWD with the 2.0 while we were in Maui this March and used it for a full week. It had just under 10,000 miles and looked like a typical rental, so my expectations were low. After a few hundred miles, it fully grew on me including the exterior styling.

The Kona is a great city car — small, easy to maneuver, and simple to park in Hawaii’s tiny spaces but also comfortable enough for long-distance driving, especially with a trim such as the Limited. The CVT was a huge surprise. I thought it was a smooth automatic until I later learned it was a CVT. It can simulates seven shifts in manual mode. Easily the best CVT I’ve driven.

The 2.0 isn’t quick, but fuel economy was decent. I’d estimate around 30 mpg, which helped with gas at $5.50+. Cold starts didn’t sound great, but once warm, the engine sounded better.

Interior space is better than expected. I’m 5'11"", and the rear legroom was surprisingly good, even a little better than my 2018 Lincoln MKZ Reserve Hybrid. Cargo space handled our suitcases and a big Costco run without any issue with one of the seats folded.

My main complaints: the center console is small and open, and the key fob is bulky with nowhere to store the physical key. Otherwise, the steering wheel felt good, handling was confident, and the LED headlights were good at night. Road and wind noise were well controlled, though Maui’s roads are extremely smooth, so I can’t speak for rougher pavement.

Feature‑wise, the Kona has more tech than my MKZ and is far better equipped than my former 2019 Tucson SE. Even the infotainment has a blue‑light filter, which was a nice touch.

If the 1.6T proves reasonably reliable long‑term, a 2025+ Kona Limited is at the top of my list. This redesign exceeded my expectations in every way, and aside from fuel economy, I’d take a Kona Limited over my MKZ.",1,KONA,0
KONA,SUV,@Cal94,"i think it's kinda disappointing the kona got bigger. the old kona was an excellent hatchback for people who wanted to pretend they didn't buy a hatchback. It was a foot shorter than actual hatchbacks like the civic hatch, crosstrek/impreza, and forte5. you could fit it anywhere, and by all accounts, the kona N was a hoot to drive. or if you just wanted creature comforts, u could option it out nicer than most other small cars, which were built to lesser price points. it had a lil niche. 

googling it now, and the new kona is still small... just two inches longer than a golf GTI. but its like 5 inches taller, and it feels like this is just another baby step towards the death of the hatchback (and the small car) in north america.",4,KONA,2
