AVANTE,Sedan,@risingwind8943,"I got the Veloster N DCT over the GR and Elantra N.  (STI and Civic type R were both very expensive at the time)  (Also at the time, the Elantra had that INCREDIBLY ugly front bumper that felt like looking at dog butt.)  Very glad I picked the VN.  The Veloster doesn't push in the turns and is DEFINITELY faster on track stock.  I have also pushed it really hard and, as long as it isn't hot out, it doesn't overheat easily unless you are hammering it as hard as an actual track-only car.  I ADORE IT.  The only thing I don't like is how bad it is in the snow.  It is NOT great.  To be fair, my previous car was a WRX, which sets a VERY high standard in bad weather, but the VN is rough in snow.  Also, if you are lucky enough to get a Veloster N, DO NOT put big tires in the rear unless they are rain tires.  The back of the VN is so light it hydroplanes easily.  Forums have dozens of people who ate a guardrail because of fat back tires.  This is definitely a FWD that would benefit from a rear wing and big front splitter if you want to get wider tires.  As for how the car feels, if the WRX I had was considered a 10 on speed, 10 on handling, and 40 in bad weather, the Veloster would be a 25 on speed, 40 on handling, and 10 in weather.  If the WRX felt like a zippy car, the VN feels like a racing go kart.  The handling is obscenely sharp.  There is ZERO torque steer.  It always feels incredibly stable and planted.  My favorite thing about the car (besides the looks) would have to be its personality.  It is a little monster.  In N mode, you can FEEL that it is just foaming at the mouth to go all out.  It is an incredibly aggressive feeling car.  The DCT is set up so that it N mode, it shifts so violently that it slaps you back in your seat.  It was designed to be viscerally engaging to all of your senses.  It feels like the spiritual successor to the 07 wrx sti, which was a goon car.  I consider the Veloster N and Elantra N to be basically the same car.  If you get the Elantra N, you won't regret it.  It IS limited on performance upgrades, but there are very affordable ways to GREATLY boost the power and acceleration.  There just isn't a crazy aftermarket like the LS, Coyote, 2JZ, or K-series.  This is the kind of car where you really only do 3 things:
Tires - You can go a hair bigger, but be aware of the hydroplaning rear.  You can get much stickier tires but the stock ones are very good.
Rear motor mount - The front tires skip a lot on launch.  The rear motor mount really REALLY helps.
Piggyback ECU + Plugs - Claims range from 310hp and 330tq to 330hp and 400tq.  Both of those make the car plenty fast.
Special mention - There is a kit you can get with a bigger machined-out turbo.  It is pricey, but is the king of the upgrades at the moment.",2,ELANTRA,4
AVANTE,Sedan,@Eruizela,"The ELANTRA is solid .this from chat GTP 

""Yes, Hyundai has hired engineers and designers from BMW and other premium automakers over the years. One of the most notable hires was Albert Biermann, the former head of BMW’s M division, who joined Hyundai in 2015 and played a major role in improving Hyundai’s vehicle dynamics, performance, and engineering.

While Biermann was more involved in Hyundai’s N performance division and models like the Elantra N, his influence likely trickled down to the standard Elantra as well, particularly in handling and chassis tuning. Hyundai has also recruited talent from other luxury brands to enhance their design, materials, and engineering. So, while the Elantra itself wasn’t built by former BMW employees, their expertise likely influenced its development.""",0,ELANTRA,2
