TUCSON,SUV,@---Wade---,"My Hyundai dealer gave me a brand new 2025 Limited gas only Tucson for 45 days while I waited for a backordered part from the factory in Korea for the new PHEV  I had a contract to purchase.   There was a very limited number of PHEV Tucsons in central California at the time and I was willing to wait for the car.  Because I wanted a ""real"" transmission, a ""real"" connected drive train for all wheel drive and a PHEV I was pretty much limited to Hyundai.  BMW PHEV only comes in the larger SUV and is a great car but $40K more than the loaded PHEV Tucson.  Here are the advantages of the PHEV Tucson over the gas only.  More horse power, 33 miles EV only.  For us most local trips are under 33 miles so we stay all EV most of the time.  Here is something no one mentions.  The PHEV is about 700 lbs heaver than the gas only.  It is 400 lbs heavier than the hybrid.  This lowers the center of gravity of the vehicle.  This adds a noticeable stability  of this SUV.   It has a combined 268 horsepower.  My 1996 C4 corvette has 300hp for comparison.",3,TUCSON,0
TUCSON,SUV,@traktion9,Thank you for a concise yet detailed technical review we come to view time after time.,0,TUCSON,4
TUCSON,SUV,@ThomasACarlos,"Ahmed.... great observations.  The average viewer would never have noticed the things you do.  I come at this with the perspective of - (1) I am 6""3"" - can I fit in a compact SUV, (2) Is the seating/driving position comfortable and can I see out the front window, (3) The visibility test compared to the Forester, (4) Engine/Drivetrain reliability (and not forgetting the Theta 2 burning engine problems), (5) For limited driving, is the Hybrid worth the extra cost compared to the gas engine (but your analysis of the lame hybrid answers that), and (6) Does the car feel relatively solid or does it feel like a Tonka car?  Despite the odd body design, I think I will put this on my ""watch list.""  Thank you!!",5,TUCSON,4
