TUCSON,SUV,@user-5gu78qo27i,"Many features on modern vehicles are not well engineered for cold/freezing weather use. And on this Tuscon is a perfect example that once winter hits, you might as well turn off that feature that automatically opens the hatch if you have the key fob in your pocket. It will put undo strain on the motor, its overheat breakers and rubber seals etc etc from ice jamming it from opening or if it does open can do a lot of harm. What about when you don't want to open the rear hatch but you're merely walking by with the key fob in your pocket? Maybe the wind has just whipped up a huge dust storm in the spring from the previous winter's sanded parking lot and timing is everything. Swosh goes half the parking lot dust right into the car with the cavernous rear opening hatch and swosh, out goes the important papers you had set atop your briefcase. Maybe not even replaceable.

To be honest I really despise motorized rear hatches. The main issue is you should have an easily accessible switch on the dash just inside the driver's door where you can turn it off.

Regarding additional unforseen damage in the winter, many brands don't allow room for ice that melts on the roof, rolls back to rear top area where hatch hinges into but then freezes solid. Your motorized hatch doesn't 'see' or know the ice is there and the leverage easily overwhelms the auto sensitivity stop and then you hear steel hatch lip ice crunching as it bends the sheet metal lip, cracks the paint and quickly allows salt to do its destructive thing even earlier than usual.

These are all very real scenarios, some of which I've already witnessed. The ice crunching i managed to quickly grab hatch and overwhelm the surprisingly strong motors and then set a new auto-stop at that point but new ice dripping in and freezing still won't recognize that new opening limit .

These types of features along with many many others, are strictly for warm wx use in Cali or Arizona or Florida.",7,TUCSON,4
