TUCSON,SUV,@yxie2685,"I'm considering to buy a compact SUV. Mazda CX-5 and Hyundai Tucson are in my list. CX-5, sure, reliable without question, but tucson, a little lower price, larger inner space, stylish design are more attractive. The only concern is that reliability might be sufferior to CX-5 at hight milelage, e.g., >100k miles. I want to buy one that lasts long. Not sure 2025 Tucson can do the job. I heard that some old Tucson have engine problem at around 100k miles.",0,TUCSON,0
TUCSON,SUV,@cincy9381,"I have driven Hyundai's for years. They've always treated me fairly well. I've been considering trading in my 15 Sonata for one of these. I agree with you, not sold on the body styling lol. It's not my favorite, but as you said.... compared to the Santa Fe it's modest. The Santa Fe exterior design is a hard no for me. I've driven the gas model of this vehicle several times, and it's just dreadfully slow in my opinion. My current Sonata is the 2.0 Turbo model, and I also have a Chrysler with the pentastar v6. So I'm used to moving when I step on the gas. I'm eyeing the hybrid model as the performance is much better. It's not a race car obviously, and I don't want/expect it to be.... but it feels adaquate! Whereas... the gas engine feels significantly underpowered in my opinion. I just don't know if I'm sold on the long term reliability of Hyundai's hybrid system. I want it to last 10 years like my current Sonata has without significant issue. I've always said I'd go Toyota if I ever bought a Hybrid vehicle. My mom recently got a new Toyota Venza and I hate the seating posistion. It's way to high for me. I can't get the seat low enough. I don't know if the RAV4 is the same way or not. That would be a hard pass for me on the RAV also if it was.",0,TUCSON,0
TUCSON,SUV,@postive-vibes,Is it too much to add a rear wiper?,0,TUCSON,0
TUCSON,SUV,@saraafrasiabi-s4x,"Haha not going to lie — the exterior isn’t the best at first glance, but once you get inside, it feels surprisingly luxurious and your perspective starts to shift. For the price, you’re getting serious bang for your buck. And since you spend most of your time inside the car, the interior quality and tech features matter way more than what others think about the outside. Plus, you really can’t beat Hyundai’s warranty, excellent safety ratings/features, and the low maintenance cost compared to European luxury cars.",0,TUCSON,2
