INSTER,SUV,@medman36,"Nice video! You beat Fully Charged for a first review of  an Inster in the UK! Sounds very good actually. Very unfortunate hyundai decided to make 3 trims. I think trim 2 makes most sense but to scale up the price to 27000 punds makes no sense, even in EV terms. For 15000-23000 euros I can get a first or second generation hyundai kona electric, bigger more hp with almost all the same featires for less. I do prefer the Inster for reason of size and practicality without losing the main tech and saftey features and getting that movable rear seat makes so much sense. But I can't understand hyundai making this 4000 pund difference for those few relevant reatirws to make them as standard. To me it is playing with fire. And these trims makes me somewhat demotivated on the Inster trim business proposition. If hyundai would sell it for 20000 euros ot would compete with the outgoing older models of the Kona electric, which are still very interesting second hand cars. To me it makes the inster a sale for the right car at the wrong time. Bit I do think we need more and better compact EVs and to me the inster makes the most sense and is more interesting than the Citroen in my view. Despite the cheaper price the eC3 makes less sense to me as an affordable EV.",0,INSTER,4
