INSTER,SUV,@javiskii,"Matt, I'm going to use you as a scapegoat, I know this ain't what you meant and I'm sorry, but I need to scream into the void.

""It feels cheap"" - cos it is. It's expensive for a cheap car, but is electric and comes from Korea, so hyundai probably won't be earning much from this. If we want to save cheap cars, we need to embrace the feel of cheapness on them. This ain't a 60K+ car, it doesn't need to feel like one",0,INSTER,0
INSTER,SUV,@kmckenzie2461,"Why do we not get these neat vehicles in the USA.  Well I guess cause everyone wants massively overpriced huge SUVs.  Makes no sense.  These more normal sized vehicles you get so much for your money.  Who needs an almost 10,000 lb GMC Hummer EV!!!  So many people in the USA have been priced out of new cars because of the massive price hikes.

My first brand new car I paid $10,500.00 for with tax title and tags and it was a 2002 Kia Rio Sedan 
5 Speed with optional power steering, optional A/C and Optional CD Player audio unit.  I had many new cars in between but cast forward to 2017 I bought a brand new 2017 Mitsubishi Mirage G4 SE top trim loaded with push start, heated seats, remote start, apple car play everything and its MSRP was $18,115.00 and I got it for under $13,000.00 brand new for the top trim.  Fast forward several more years and a few cars later I bought another new 2021 Mitsubishi Mirage SE hatch loaded top trim with all the features and modern forward collision systems, auto high beams, lane departure, heated seats, push start, led head and tail lights and its MSRP was $19,710.00 I believe and I only got around $500.00 off MSRP.  Its a shame how new car prices have climbed and climbed and discounts of the old days are gone.  I know a lot of this happen due to and after covid but damn its ridiculous.  

Now the last new small cars left in the USA are the Mitsubishi Mirage and Mirage G4 and they are done after 2024 then only leaving the 2024-2025 Nissan Versa as the last standing Subcompact Sedan which it is said to be cancelled after 2025.  

No more getting a loaded top trim new car for under $20,000.00 nope now for 2025 its finding one starting out at a base price of $21,000.00 to $24,000.00 and running $25,000.00 to $30,0000.00 plus for a top trim loaded model.  Man has the market changed.  It will mostly be crossovers like a Hyundai Venue, Kia Soul, Nissan Kicks, Chevy Trax, Buick Envista  and so on but there are still sedans in that range too like the Nissan Versa (loaded top trim SR model for under $23,000.00) Nissan Sentra, Hyundai Elantra, VW Jetta, Kia K4 (super sharp), Mazda 3 and so on.  Its just a shame.  These times after Covid have just skyrocketed prices on everything but especially in the auto industry with larger prices, larger vehicles, and longer loans when really its harder now for people to afford more yet they do it and have higher and higher car payments!  

I purchased a brand new top trim 2023 Nissan Kicks SR with the Premium Package in October 2023 and it had an MSRP of $26,130.00 which was a good price for all the features.  Now again it was the top trim SR with the added $1,390.00 Premium Package, $395.00 Boulder Gray Pearl Paint, $225.00 or so for the carpeted floor mats and cargo mat, and around $225.00 for the Splash Guards and all this came to an MSRP of $26,130.00 and for all the safety features like 10 airbags, forward collision mitigation with pedestrian detection, rear back up collision mitigation, auto high beams, lane departure warning, haptic steering wheel, rear cross traffic alert, blind spot warning, dynamic control module and all the convenience features like push button start, adaptive cruise, 360 surround view cameras, 8 speaker bose audio, prinatex leathertte 3 tone seating, electronic parking brake, led headlights, led fog lights, led tail lights, 8 inch touch screen with apple car play and android auto, Nissan Connect app with SOS Telematics and Wifi, remote start on key fob too as well as app, digital gauges, alloy wheels and much more.  Great price for what you get but now the new 2025 redesigned Nissan Kicks has gotten a lil bigger, added optional AWD, and a panoramic roof and a few other things and now when you option out a top trim 2025 Nissan Kicks SR Premium AWD your are near $33,000.00!  A $7,000.00 jump!  Even if you keep it FWD its still an over $5,000.00 jump!  Quite a jump!  Its just s hame the way the market is going.",0,INSTER,4
