INSTER,SUV,@martythebeaglenese9023,"And as with any new ""affordable"" EV launching in 2025, videos like this will tell you how cheap this car is, because Hyundai was careful to only provide the entry-model price . And then show off the absolute decked-out top spec model that costs £4000-5000 more than the base model. In the hopes to draw in viewers with the low price claim, and then show them all the extras that - if you wanna get those - will set you back the same ludicrous amount of money that EVs have always done. It wouldn't be surprising that Hyundai's conditions for allowing the testing of this was a demand to spend many minutes specifically highlighting features not found in the base model; like the 3 minute section devoted to the rear seats and boot.

A partial list this things NOT included in the affordable version of this car:
The foldable front seats.
Adjustable rear seats.
Heat pump.
Heated seats.
Heated steering wheel.
Blind spot mirrors.
Driver armrest
LED lights
Front parking sensor
Rain sensor.
Wireless phone charging

This car is not the affordable choice it's being advertised as: In order to get anything even remotely near expectations of equipment and tech from a brand new 2025 car, this vehicle is just as over-priced as EVs have been for years.",0,INSTER,0
